"""
MKT Christ Commentary — John chapters 19–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-john-19-21.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text for quoting)
- data/parallels/john.json (absorbed: Isa 53:7 on 19:9; Ps 22:18 on 19:24; Ps 69:21 on 19:28–29;
  Ps 34:20 and Exod 12:46 on 19:36; Zech 12:10 on 19:37)
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (tetelestai/G5055, agapaō/G25, phileō/G5368, pneuma/G4151)

Key decisions in this range:
- Author referred to as "the Evangelist"; Jesus as "Jesus" or "the Son"
- 19:14 (sixth hour, Preparation of Passover): classified as direct type — the hour the Passover
  lambs are slaughtered in the temple is the hour Pilate's final judgment is pronounced; the Evangelist
  marks this synchronism deliberately
- 19:30 (tetelestai): classified as direct revelation — teleō (G5055) has the commercial/forensic
  sense of "paid in full / completed"; the gift of pneuma simultaneously signals new creation
- 19:34 (blood and water): classified as revelation of God — the Evangelist insists on the eyewitness
  quality; the theological weight (sacramental, eschatological) noted without over-determining it
- 19:36 (Exod 12:46 / Ps 34:20): classified as direct type + direct fulfillment — both texts cited
  as fulfilled; the Passover-lamb identification is the Evangelist's own typological argument
- 20:22 (breathed on them): classified as direct type — the deliberate echo of Gen 2:7 marks the
  resurrection as new creation; the Spirit-breath of the new humanity
- 20:28 (Thomas's confession "My Lord and my God"): classified as direct revelation — the highest
  explicit Christological confession in John; echoes Ps 35:23 (LXX) but functions as more than OT echo
- 21:9, 15–17 (charcoal fire + triple commission): classified as direct revelation — the charcoal fire
  (anthrakia, only at 18:18 and 21:9 in NT) links the denial scene to the restoration scene; the
  threefold "do you love me?" reverses the threefold denial precisely
- 21:15 agapaō vs. phileō: both words appear; not classifying this as a sharp semantic distinction
  (dispute_level differs; the Evangelist may be using them as synonyms in this context) — noted in
  the commentary without over-pressing the distinction
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOHN = {
  "19": {
    "1": '<p>A shadow: Pilate\'s flogging of Jesus — ordered before any sentence of death, apparently as a lesser punishment intended to satisfy the crowd — is the enacted form of Isaiah 53:5: "by his wounds we are healed." The Servant who bears the punishment meant for others undergoes the lash not because he is guilty but because the suffering has a substitutionary purpose. The Evangelist does not quote Isaiah here (he will quote it in the parallel summary at 12:38), but the resonance is structural: the one whose flogging should produce acquittal instead produces the demand for crucifixion.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: the soldiers\' mock coronation — crown of thorns, purple robe — is the Evangelist\'s deepest irony. They intend contempt; they are performing the truth. The one they dress as a pretend king is the king. The purple robe that belongs to royalty is placed on the one who is, by right, the King of kings (Rev 19:16). The crown of thorns echoes the curse of Genesis 3:18 ("thorns and thistles it will produce for you") — the Adamic curse is placed on the second Adam\'s head. He bears what the earth produced under the curse so that the curse can be broken.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "Hail, king of the Jews!" — spoken in mockery — is the acclamation that history will vindicate. Every knee that did not bow in recognition before the cross will bow at the final revelation (Phil 2:10). The slaps and the salute are the inversion of the honor the Son deserves; the cross will be followed by an exaltation in which every tongue will confess what the soldiers\' lips were performing in contempt. The Evangelist places the mock coronation before the crucifixion so that the reader sees the crown, the robe, and the throne (the cross) together.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "I find no basis for a charge against him" — Pilate\'s triple declaration of innocence (18:38; 19:4; 19:6) is the Gentile judge\'s unwitting testimony to the spotless Lamb. The Passover lamb was to be examined and found without defect (Exod 12:5); the Roman governor performs this examination and declares the result. The legal procedure that should acquit instead condemns — not because the verdict is wrong but because the one condemned is accepting condemnation for others. Pilate\'s innocence-declaration is part of the Evangelist\'s case that what happens at Golgotha is substitutionary.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: "Here is the man!" (<em>Idou ho anthrōpos</em>) — Pilate\'s words are the Evangelist\'s Christological announcement. "The man" who appears crowned with thorns is the Son of Man of Daniel 7:13 who comes before the Ancient of Days to receive the kingdom. But in John\'s inversion, the Son of Man comes before a human court before he comes before the divine throne. "Ecce homo" becomes the presentation of the one who is both representative human (the second Adam bearing the crown of thorns) and the divine Son being offered for the world.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: the chief priests\' demand — "Crucify! Crucify!" — and Pilate\'s response, "You take him and crucify him," is the abdication of justice that nevertheless enacts the divine purpose. The Evangelist has been tracking the authorities\' decision to kill Jesus since 11:47–53 (Caiaphas\'s prophecy that "one man should die for the people"). The shouting at the praetorium is the ugly human face of what Caiaphas stated as cold political calculation. Behind both is the Father\'s own plan: the Son is given over to death so that scattered children may be gathered (11:52).</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct revelation: "We have a law, and according to that law he must die, because he claimed to be the Son of God." The charge is the Christological truth. The accusation the leaders frame as blasphemy is the exact identity the Gospel has been establishing since 1:1. He is the Son of God (1:34; 1:49; 3:16–18; 5:25; 10:36; 11:4). Their law calls for death for the blasphemer who falsely claims divine status; Jesus is not a blasphemer but the one of whom the law was inadequate to speak. The charge that condemns him is the truth about him — the deepest irony of the trial narrative.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "When Pilate heard this, he was even more afraid." The pagan governor\'s fear at the claim of divine sonship is the authentic response to the disclosure — more honest than the priests\' controlled hostility. Pilate senses that something beyond ordinary justice is at stake, that the one before him may not be what he appears. His fear does not produce the response fear should produce (recognition and release); it produces deeper ambivalence. The Evangelist shows that even those who glimpse the truth about Christ can refuse to act on it.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct type: Jesus gives Pilate no answer to "Where do you come from?" — the question of origin that the Gospel has been answering since 1:1 ("in the beginning was the Word... the Word was with God"). The silence before the judge activates Isaiah 53:7: "he was oppressed and afflicted, yet he did not open his mouth; he was led like a lamb to the slaughter, and as a sheep before its shearers is silent, so he did not open his mouth." The Servant\'s silence before his accusers is not weakness but the deliberate restraint of the one who has already answered every question with his person and works. There is nothing more to say.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "Don\'t you realize I have power either to free you or to crucify you?" Pilate\'s claim of ultimate authority over life and death is the natural claim of Roman power. Jesus\' answer in v11 will subvert it entirely: the authority Pilate claims was given to him from above — it is derivative, delegated, and temporary. The scene is the enacted demonstration of the principle Jesus stated in 10:17–18: "No one takes my life from me, but I lay it down of my own accord." Pilate believes he is exercising power; he is participating in a drama whose script was written before the foundation of the world.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "You would have no power over me if it were not given to you from above." The sovereignty of the Son over his own death is stated directly to the one who believes he controls it. The authority to crucify Jesus was given — by the Father, through the structures of human history and Roman governance — for the purpose of the cross. This does not make Judas or Caiaphas or Pilate innocent instruments; Jesus distinguishes degrees of guilt ("the greater sin" belongs to those who handed him over). But the entire proceeding is within the Father\'s governance, and the Son knows it.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "If you let this man go, you are no friend of Caesar." The political trap closes. Pilate, who wanted to release Jesus, is forced into the logic of imperial loyalty: to protect an innocent man who is accused of claiming kingship is to risk being reported as a traitor. The world\'s system — honor, loyalty, self-preservation, political calculation — is deployed against the innocent king. The Evangelist is showing how the prince of this world (12:31) operates through human systems: through fear of Caesar, through the machinery of honor-shame, through the threat to career and standing.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: Pilate brings Jesus to the "Stone Pavement" (<em>Lithostroton</em> / Aramaic Gabbatha) and sits on the judgment seat. The Evangelist\'s specific notation of the location — judicial, elevated, public — is the setting for the final verdict. The one who sits on the judgment seat to condemn is himself condemned by history; the one condemned before the seat will sit on the throne (Rev 3:21 — the one who overcomes will sit with Christ on his throne). The scene anticipates its own reversal: the judgment seat of Pilate prefigures the judgment seat of Christ (2 Cor 5:10).</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct type: "It was the day of Preparation of the Passover; it was about noon." The Evangelist\'s precise chronological notation is Christological. Noon on the day of Preparation (Nisan 14) was the hour when the Passover lambs began to be slaughtered in the temple. At the moment Pilate presents Jesus — "Here is your king" — the lambs are being killed for the Passover feast. The typological identification the Baptist made at the Gospel\'s opening ("the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world," 1:29) is enacted in calendar time: the Lamb is being condemned at exactly the hour the temple lambs are being killed.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: "We have no king but Caesar." The chief priests\' declaration is the apostasy the Old Testament warned against. Israel\'s demand for a human king in 1 Samuel 8 was the rejection of the LORD\'s kingship ("they have rejected me as their king," 1 Sam 8:7). Here the leaders of Israel formally disclaim the kingship of God\'s own Son in favor of the Roman emperor — the furthest possible point from the theocratic covenant. The irony is total: the custodians of the Davidic covenant, who await the Son of David, reject him when he stands before them, preferring the king of the Gentiles to the King of Israel.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "Finally Pilate handed him over to them to be crucified." The handing over (<em>paredōken</em>) is the word that runs through the passion: Judas hands Jesus over to the priests (18:2, 5); the priests hand him to Pilate (18:30, 35); Pilate hands him to be crucified. The chain of "handing over" is the human side of what Paul articulates in Romans 8:32: "He who did not spare his own Son but gave him up (<em>paredōken</em>) for us all." The Father\'s giving-up of the Son runs through and beneath every human act of betrayal and judicial capitulation. The Son is given over by the Father\'s love precisely through the machinery of human failure.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A shadow: "Carrying his own cross, he went out to the place of the Skull." The image of Jesus carrying the instrument of his own death activates the shadow of Isaac carrying the wood for the burnt offering up Mount Moriah (Gen 22:6: "Abraham took the wood for the burnt offering and placed it on his son Isaac"). The son carries the wood; the father has provided the lamb (Gen 22:8); the place is a mountain near Jerusalem. The Evangelist does not quote Genesis 22, but the structural parallel is the Christological argument the NT makes throughout: Isaac on Moriah is the type; Jesus at Golgotha is the antitype. The ram provided at the last moment in Genesis is replaced by the Son who is himself the provision.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "There they crucified him, and with him two others — one on each side and Jesus in the middle." Isaiah 53:12 — "he was numbered with the transgressors" — is enacted in the placement. Jesus is not crucified alone but positioned between criminals, fulfilling the Servant\'s identification with those he came to save. Luke\'s account of the penitent thief (Luke 23:39–43) makes the fulfillment explicit; the Evangelist\'s placement of Jesus "in the middle" underscores it geometrically. The one who is the center of all history is placed at the center of the row of the condemned.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct revelation: "JESUS OF NAZARETH, THE KING OF THE JEWS." Pilate\'s inscription — meant as a political insult, a mockery of Jewish messianic hope — is the Gospel\'s final public proclamation of who Jesus is. The Evangelist has been building toward this statement since 1:45 ("We have found the one Moses wrote about in the Law... Jesus of Nazareth"). The title on the cross is the title that is true: he is the King of the Jews and, through the Jews, the king of the world (4:42 — "the Savior of the world"). The cross is the throne; the inscription is the royal title.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "the sign was written in Aramaic, Latin and Greek." The three languages of first-century Judea — the sacred language of Jewish scripture, the official language of Roman power, the universal language of Hellenistic culture — all declare the kingship of the crucified Jesus. The Evangelist\'s notation that "many of the Jews read this sign" is the Christological announcement going public: the title of the crucified king is published in every language relevant to his world. The universal scope of the proclamation (to all peoples and cultures) anticipates what the resurrection will make explicitly universal.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: the chief priests\' protest — "do not write The King of the Jews, but that this man claimed to be king of the Jews" — and Pilate\'s refusal ("what I have written, I have written") is the Evangelist\'s irony at its most concentrated. Pilate, who has been bullied through the entire trial, digs in at exactly this point. He will not change the inscription. The Evangelist presents this as providential: the title that stands is the true one. Human stubbornness becomes the instrument of divine declaration. The cross announces the kingship that the leaders refuse to acknowledge.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "What I have written, I have written." Pilate\'s finality at this point — when he has capitulated on everything else — is the Evangelist\'s signal of something fixed. The inscription will not be revised. In John\'s Gospel, this single act of Pilate\'s stubbornness becomes the unwitting permanent testimony of a pagan official to the true identity of the crucified. The permanence of the written word ("it is written" — <em>gegraptai</em> — is the formula for Scripture throughout John) applies here: the cross\'s title is fixed and cannot be recalled.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: the seamless undergarment — woven in one piece from top to bottom — that the soldiers divide by lot is a detail the Evangelist preserves because it will fulfill Scripture (v24). The garment\'s seamlessness has generated centuries of allegorical reading (the unity of the church, the priestly tunic). The Evangelist\'s own interpretation is strictly Christological: this happened so that the scripture might be fulfilled. The seamless robe is significant not for what it symbolizes but for what happens to it — it fulfills the Psalm. But the seamlessness also underscores the integrity of the sacrifice: what belongs to the crucified is not destroyed but distributed, preserved, and contested over.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct fulfillment: Psalm 22:18 — "They divided my clothes among them and cast lots for my garment" — is quoted and explicitly applied by the Evangelist to the soldiers\' action. Psalm 22 is the psalm of the abandoned righteous sufferer who cries "My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?" (v1 — cited by Jesus from the cross in the Synoptics) and whose suffering is described in detail (vv14–18) that the passion narrative fulfills with remarkable specificity: the mocking onlookers (vv7–8), the pierced hands and feet (v16), and here the divided garments (v18). The Evangelist\'s explicit citation marks the crucifixion as the climactic fulfillment of the righteous sufferer\'s Psalm.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: the women who stand near the cross — including his mother — are the faithful witnesses at the moment of the Son\'s death. While the male disciples have scattered (with the exception of the Beloved Disciple), the women remain. The Evangelist names four: his mother, his mother\'s sister, Mary of Clopas, and Mary Magdalene. Their faithfulness at the cross will be rewarded with the first witness of the resurrection (Mary Magdalene, 20:14–18). The presence of the mother at the death of the Son evokes the Simeon prophecy (Luke 2:35 — "a sword will pierce your own soul too") and the deepest form of maternal love.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "Woman, here is your son." The dying Son\'s care for his mother — even from the cross — is the expression of the love that "goes to the end" (<em>eis telos</em>, 13:1). But the act is more than filial duty. By committing his mother to the Beloved Disciple, Jesus is constituting a new family. The address "Woman" — used also at Cana (2:4) — signals a transition: she is no longer primarily his mother in the biological sense but a member of the new community of those who love him. The cross is the moment when the eschatological family (those who do the will of the Father, Matt 12:50) is formally established.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "Here is your mother." The Beloved Disciple takes her into his own home — <em>eis ta idia</em> (into his own things/home) — the same phrase used in 1:11 ("his own did not receive him"). Those who did not receive him at his coming now become his family through his death. The Beloved Disciple represents all disciples who take the mother of the crucified into their homes, their lives, and their communities. The cross creates the new household of God: a community constituted by love for and belonging to the Son.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "so that Scripture would be fulfilled, Jesus said, \'I am thirsty.\'" The Evangelist explicitly frames the declaration of thirst as Scripture-fulfillment — most likely Psalm 69:21 ("they gave me vinegar for my thirst"), which the parallel data confirms, and possibly Psalm 22:15 ("my strength is dried up like a potsherd; and my tongue cleaveth to my jaws"). The Son who is the source of living water (4:14; 7:37–38) thirsts on the cross. The inversion is the atonement in miniature: the one who gives water takes vinegar; the source of life enters death; the fullness of God empties itself so that the emptied may be filled.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct type: "they soaked a sponge in it, put the sponge on a stalk of the hyssop plant, and lifted it to Jesus\' lips." The Evangelist\'s specific notation of hyssop is Christological. Hyssop was the plant used to apply the Passover lamb\'s blood to the doorposts (Exod 12:22); it appears in Psalm 51:7 as the instrument of purification ("cleanse me with hyssop, and I will be clean"). The hyssop branch that carries the final drink to the Passover Lamb is the same plant that applied the Passover blood for Israel\'s protection. The instrument of purification now touches the Lamb himself at the moment of his death — the final gesture of the Passover typology.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A direct revelation: "It is finished" (<em>Tetelestai</em>). The verb <em>teleō</em> (G5055) carries both completion and discharge-of-obligation: the work is accomplished, the debt is paid. The Evangelist has built toward this word through the Gospel\'s entire movement. The Father\'s mission ("to do the will of him who sent me and to finish his work," 4:34) is now declared complete. The "hour" that "had not yet come" for most of the Gospel has come and been fulfilled. Then: "he bowed his head and gave up his spirit" (<em>paredōken to pneuma</em>). The same word <em>paredōken</em> ("gave up / handed over") that described the Father\'s giving over of the Son (Rom 8:32) and Pilate\'s handing over (v16) is used for the Son\'s own final act: he surrenders the spirit deliberately, at the moment of completion.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: the Jewish leaders\' concern for Sabbath purity — requesting that the bodies be removed before sundown — is the religious scrupulosity that sought Jesus\' death now focused on the proper observance of the day following his death. The Evangelist does not editorialize on the irony; he simply notes it. The breaking of legs to hasten death is the procedure the Sabbath concern requires — and it will produce the fulfillment of Scripture (v36) by its very avoidance in Jesus\' case.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: the soldiers break the legs of the two men crucified with Jesus. For them, death comes by fracture. For Jesus, the distinction will be total: he is already dead (v33); no bone will be broken. The two who were crucified with him — the transgressors of Isaiah 53:12 — die by the soldiers\' action; the one in the middle dies on his own terms, at the moment of <em>tetelestai</em>, surrendering the spirit rather than having life crushed out by further violence. The contrast of deaths is the Evangelist\'s way of marking the crucifixion as unique in kind.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "But when they came to Jesus and found that he was already dead, they did not break his legs." The discovery of death without breaking is the Evangelist\'s pivot toward Scripture fulfillment. The death has already occurred — at the moment Jesus chose, at the word <em>tetelestai</em>. The soldiers\' restraint is not mercy but recognition of accomplished fact. The result is that both Scripture citations in vv36–37 will be fulfilled: no bone broken (Passover lamb / Ps 34:20), and the one pierced (Zech 12:10). The passive instruments of the passion are unwitting fulfillors of the prophetic word.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "one of the soldiers pierced Jesus\' side with a spear, bringing a sudden flow of blood and water." The Evangelist insists on the eyewitness reality of this detail in the very next verse, which is unusual — indicating the theological weight he places on it. The blood and water have been read in multiple registers: as medical evidence (post-mortem fluid separation — real physical death, against any docetic reading); as sacramental (blood of the Eucharist, water of baptism — the two dominical sacraments flowing from the crucified body); as eschatological (Ezek 47; the river of life flowing from the temple, which Jesus identified as his body at 2:21). The Evangelist preserves the detail without resolving the registers — the reader encounters a fact that carries more meaning than any single reading exhausts.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "The man who saw it has given testimony, and his testimony is true. He knows that he tells the truth, and he testifies so that you also may believe." The Beloved Disciple\'s witness at this precise point — the piercing and the blood and water — is the ground on which the Gospel\'s case for Christ rests. The crucifixion is not narrated from a distance but witnessed at close range by one who stood under the cross (v26). The Evangelist\'s insistence on eyewitness testimony for this detail elevates it to the level of the foundational evidence for the incarnation and death: the Word became real flesh, died a real death, and the one who saw it says so.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A direct fulfillment and direct type: "Not one of his bones will be broken" fulfills two texts simultaneously. Psalm 34:20 ("he protects all his bones, not one of them will be broken") is the righteous sufferer\'s protection extended to the suffering Christ. Exodus 12:46 ("do not break any of the bones") is the Passover lamb regulation — the lamb killed for Israel\'s protection was not to have its bones broken. The Evangelist presents Jesus as the fulfillment of both: the protected righteous one and the slain Passover lamb whose integrity must be preserved. The Passover typology that has structured the entire Gospel (1:29; 19:14) reaches its final fulfillment point here.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "They will look on the one they have pierced" — Zechariah 12:10 is cited as fulfilled in the piercing of Jesus\' side. Zechariah\'s vision speaks of a day when the house of David and the inhabitants of Jerusalem will look on the one they pierced and mourn for him as for an only child. The Evangelist applies the verse to the soldiers\' spear-thrust and the community who witnesses it. The Revelation will apply it eschatologically to the final manifestation of the crucified king: "Look, he is coming with the clouds, and every eye will see him, even those who pierced him" (Rev 1:7). The piercing at Golgotha is the historical event; the universal looking-upon is the eschatological event it anticipates.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A revelation of God: Joseph of Arimathea, who was "a disciple of Jesus, but secretly because he feared the Jewish leaders," comes forward at the moment of greatest danger — after the crucifixion, when associating with the condemned man carries maximum risk — to claim the body. The Evangelist presents the death of Jesus as the event that draws the secret disciples out of hiding. The cross, which drove others away, draws Joseph and Nicodemus (v39) toward the body. The same gravity the Evangelist described in 12:32 ("I, when I am lifted up from the earth, will draw all people to myself") is already operating at the foot of the cross.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A revelation of God: Nicodemus — who "had first come to Jesus at night" (3:1–2) — comes now in the daylight of the crucifixion, bearing seventy-five pounds of myrrh and aloes. The man who came to Jesus in darkness comes to his dead body in the open. The Evangelist\'s reference to the nighttime visit is not incidental: the one who came in the night (3:19 — "people loved darkness") comes out of the darkness at the foot of the cross. The death of Jesus is the light that brings him into the day. The extravagance of seventy-five pounds of burial spice is the costly devotion of a man who has finally come out of the shadows to honor the one he believed in secretly.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A revelation of God: "Taking Jesus\' body, the two of them wrapped it, with the spices, in strips of linen. This was in accordance with Jewish burial customs." The care of the burial — two members of the Sanhedrin (Joseph and Nicodemus), a garden tomb, costly spices, proper linen wrappings — is the Evangelist\'s signal that this is a real death receiving real burial. The resurrection will be from an actual tomb with actual grave clothes. But the spices also echo the anointing at Bethany (12:3 — Mary\'s nard for burial); the women who planned to bring spices (Mark 16:1) will find the task already done. The burial is the preparation for the resurrection; what is laid in the tomb will be raised.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A shadow: "At the place where Jesus was crucified, there was a garden, and in the garden a new tomb." The Evangelist\'s notation of the garden is theologically charged. The story of humanity began in a garden (Eden, Gen 2–3) and was broken in a garden. The death that entered through the first garden is now being met in another garden at the place of the skull. The Evangelist will develop the garden motif in chapter 20: Mary Magdalene will mistake the risen Jesus for "the gardener" (20:15) — a misrecognition that is also a recognition, since the risen Christ is the new gardener of the new creation, the one who tends the restored garden from which death has been expelled.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A revelation of God: "because it was the Jewish day of Preparation and since the tomb was nearby, they laid Jesus there." The proximity of the tomb — a new tomb in a nearby garden — is presented as providential practicality. But the Evangelist\'s Gospel does not do coincidence; everything is purposeful. The new tomb (no one had ever been laid there) is the appropriate resting place for the one through whom all things are made new. The one who said "I am the resurrection and the life" (11:25) is laid in the ground as the seed that must fall and die before it rises to produce many seeds (12:24). The burial is the nadir before the glorification.</p>'
  },
  "20": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "Early on the first day of the week." The Evangelist\'s chronological marker is theologically exact. The resurrection occurs on the first day — not the seventh day of Sabbath rest, but the first day, the day of beginning. Genesis 1:1–2 begins "in the beginning" with the first day of creation; John 1:1 echoes it ("in the beginning was the Word"). The resurrection is the beginning of the new creation. The seventh day of creation was rest after the completion of the work; Jesus rested in the tomb on the Sabbath after declaring the work complete (<em>tetelestai</em>). The first day of the new week is the first day of the new creation.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: Mary Magdalene\'s report — "they have taken the Lord out of the tomb, and we don\'t know where they have put him" — is the pre-understanding that the resurrection must overcome. She interprets the empty tomb as grave robbery, not resurrection. The Evangelist preserves this misunderstanding as the authentic starting point for all resurrection faith: the empty tomb alone does not produce belief. What Mary needs — and what she will receive in v16 — is not the empty tomb but the living person. The resurrection faith that the Gospel calls for is not a conclusion drawn from evidence but an encounter with the risen Christ himself.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "Peter and the other disciple started for the tomb." The two disciples who will play complementary roles throughout the resurrection and epilogue — Peter the actor, the Beloved Disciple the contemplator — run together toward the evidence. The resurrection is not merely a spiritual conviction; it generates physical response. The disciples run. The Evangelist\'s detail of the running underscores the urgency that the news of resurrection produces: you do not walk calmly to investigate the possibility that death has been defeated.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "the other disciple outran Peter and reached the tomb first." The Beloved Disciple arrives first but does not enter. The sequence — arrival, hesitation, entry — is the Evangelist\'s way of slowing the reader down at the moment of the resurrection discovery. The race to the tomb mirrors the urgency of faith\'s response; the pause at the entrance mirrors the awe that the resurrection properly commands. Faith reaches the resurrection site before it fully enters into the reality of what has happened.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: the Beloved Disciple bends down and sees the linen clothes lying there but does not go in. The linen grave clothes are visible from outside — the tomb is not violently disturbed. The orderly arrangement of the burial materials in an empty space is the first physical evidence that what has happened is not grave robbery. A thief does not fold the napkin (v7); the grave clothes are still there, but the body is not. The resurrection has passed through the burial wrappings like the risen body will pass through locked doors (v19).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: Simon Peter, arriving second, goes straight in — the Evangelist\'s consistent portrait of Peter as the one who acts where others pause. Peter sees "the strips of linen lying there" — the burial wrappings in place, flat, deflated of the body they once enclosed. The implication of what he sees will take the next few verses to become clear: the body has not been removed in the wrappings but has somehow left the wrappings behind, passing through them as the risen body passes through sealed enclosures.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "the cloth that had been wrapped around Jesus\' head... was still lying in its place, separate from the linen." The separate placement of the head-cloth is the detail that clinches the Beloved Disciple\'s faith (v8). The folded or rolled-up cloth "in its place" is not the evidence of hurried removal but of orderly, deliberate departure. The risen body left its grave clothes behind with the same deliberateness with which the Son had laid down his life: "No one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord" (10:18). He laid down his life; he lays aside the burial clothes; he exits the tomb on his own terms.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct revelation: "he saw and believed." The Beloved Disciple\'s belief at the sight of the grave clothes — before seeing the risen Christ — is the first resurrection faith in John\'s Gospel. It rests on the physical evidence of the orderly empty tomb and is completed only later by encounter with the risen Christ. The Evangelist does not specify what exactly he believed; v9 clarifies that the full scriptural understanding was still coming. The faith that begins here is real but incomplete — it will be filled out by the appearances of the next forty days, by the Spirit\'s illumination (14:26), and by the retrospective reading of Scripture.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "(They still did not understand from Scripture that Jesus had to rise from the dead.)" The Evangelist\'s parenthetical is his honest acknowledgment that the resurrection was not anticipated by the disciples — even though the Scriptures pointed to it. The key texts (Ps 16:10 — "you will not abandon me to the realm of the dead"; Isa 53:10–12 — the Servant\'s vindication after suffering; Hos 6:2 — "on the third day he will restore us") were present in the tradition, but their Christological application was not yet visible. The resurrection itself will be the hermeneutical key: the risen Christ will open the Scriptures to his disciples (Luke 24:27, 45), and the Spirit will remind them of everything (John 14:26). Scripture that pointed to the resurrection is understood as pointing to the resurrection only after the resurrection happens.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then the disciples went back to where they were staying." The return home after the empty-tomb discovery is the disciples\' moment of incomplete resolution. They have seen the evidence; the Beloved Disciple has believed; but they do not yet fully understand. The Evangelist\'s narrative does not rush toward the appearance — it pauses at this point of suspended understanding. The resurrection faith that will become the church\'s foundation is not yet fully formed; it is gestating in the disciples who have seen and begun to believe but who need the appearances that follow.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: Mary stands outside the tomb weeping. She has not entered, has not seen the grave clothes, has not believed. Her weeping is the grief of absolute loss — the one she loved is gone, and now even his body is missing. The Evangelist gives the most extended and personal resurrection appearance to the one who was the last to leave and the first to encounter the risen Christ. The depth of her grief is the depth of her love (12:3 — the woman who anointed his feet); the depth of her grief is the measure of the joy her name will produce (v16).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A shadow: "two angels in white, seated where Jesus\' body had been, one at the head and the other at the foot." The two angels seated at head and foot of the burial space evoke the cherubim on the ark of the covenant — one at each end of the mercy seat (Exod 25:18–22; 37:7–9). The ark was the place where God\'s presence dwelt with Israel; the cherubim flanked the space above which the LORD spoke. The body of Jesus, which the Evangelist has identified as the new temple (2:21), has left its resting place attended by the same angelic markers that flanked the most holy place in the tabernacle. The empty space between the angels is the mercy seat from which the risen Christ has departed.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "They have taken my Lord away, and I don\'t know where they have put him." Mary\'s response to the angels\' question — "Why are you crying?" — is the articulation of resurrection grief: the Lord is absent, and she does not know where. She has lost, first, his presence in life; then, his body in death; now she fears the loss even of the tomb. The threefold loss mirrors the disciples\' threefold abandonment: dispersed at the arrest, absent at the cross (except the Beloved Disciple), now absent from the empty tomb. Mary alone remains — faithful to the end.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "she turned around and saw Jesus standing there, but she did not realize that it was Jesus." The non-recognition is the resurrection\'s epistemological challenge. The risen Jesus is recognizably the same person (v20 — the disciples rejoice when they see him; the disciples on the road to Emmaus recognize him in the breaking of bread) and yet different in some way that makes immediate recognition impossible without an additional act — a word, a gesture, a name. The resurrection body is continuous with but not identical to the pre-crucifixion body. Mary\'s non-recognition is not failure of perception but the appropriate first response to the unprecedented.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A shadow: "Thinking he was the gardener." Mary\'s misidentification of the risen Christ as the gardener is the Evangelist\'s final garden motif. The first garden (Gen 2–3) was tended by humanity under God\'s oversight; the human gardeners failed and the garden was closed. The risen Christ in the garden of the resurrection is the new Adam who tends the new creation. The misidentification is wrong in its immediate reference but right in its deeper sense: the risen Jesus is the gardener of the new creation, restoring what Adam forfeited. The second Adam stands in the garden where death has been conquered, and the woman at first does not recognize him — as the second Adam restores what was broken when the first woman and man failed to recognize the goodness of what God had given.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct revelation: "Jesus said to her, \'Mary.\' She turned toward him and cried out in Aramaic, \'Rabboni!\'" The moment of recognition comes through the voice speaking her name. This is the fulfillment of Jesus\' own promise in 10:3–4: "the sheep listen to his voice. He calls his own sheep by name and leads them out... his sheep follow him because they know his voice." Mary is one of the sheep; she is called by name; she recognizes the voice. The risen Shepherd locates the lost sheep in the garden of the resurrection and calls her by name — the act of personal knowledge and love that defines the relationship between the Good Shepherd and each member of the flock.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "Do not hold on to me, for I have not yet ascended to the Father." The instruction is not a refusal of relationship but a redefinition of it. The clinging to the physical presence — the desire to hold the resurrection body in place — must give way to the new mode of relationship that the ascension will inaugurate. After the ascension, the disciples will know Christ through the Spirit (14:16–18; 16:7 — "it is for your good that I am going away"). The ascension is not absence but the transition to a more universal and permanent presence. Mary must release the resurrection body in order to receive the ascended Lord through the Spirit.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: Mary Magdalene goes to the disciples with the announcement "I have seen the Lord!" The woman who was last at the tomb becomes the first herald of the resurrection — the apostle to the apostles, as the early church will call her. The Evangelist\'s choice to make the primary resurrection witness a woman is consistent with John\'s pattern of women as exemplary disciples: the Samaritan woman (4:39), Mary of Bethany (11:32; 12:3), the women at the cross (19:25). The resurrection announcement, which the entire Gospel has been moving toward, is first spoken by a woman to the male disciples who had fled.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "Jesus came and stood among them and said, \'Peace be with you!\'" The risen Christ\'s entrance through locked doors and his greeting — <em>eirēnē hymin</em> (peace to you) — is the fulfillment of the promise he made hours earlier: "Peace I leave with you; my peace I give you... Do not let your hearts be troubled and do not be afraid" (14:27). The peace that the world could not give and that the disciples had lost at the arrest is now given in person by the risen Son. The locked doors cannot keep out the one who passes through the grave clothes and out of the sealed tomb; the risen Christ brings peace to rooms sealed with fear.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "he showed them his hands and side. The disciples were overjoyed when they saw the Lord." The resurrection body bears the marks of the crucifixion. The wounds are not hidden or erased; they are displayed as the identity marks of the risen Christ. This is the Evangelist\'s insistence on the continuity between the crucified and the risen: the one who was pierced (19:34, 37 — Zech 12:10 applied) carries the piercing into the resurrection. The joy the disciples experience is the fulfilment of 16:20–22: "your grief will turn to joy... I will see you again and you will rejoice, and no one will take away your joy."</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "As the Father has sent me, I am sending you." The mission of the disciples is constituted by the mission of the Son: the sending pattern that runs through John (the Father sends the Son, the Son sends the disciples) is formally established at the first resurrection appearance. The disciples who receive the peace of the risen Christ are immediately commissioned as the extension of his mission into the world. The Christological principle of 13:20 — "whoever accepts anyone I send accepts me; and whoever accepts me accepts the one who sent me" — is now made the foundation of the church\'s apostolic identity.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct type: "And with that he breathed on them and said, \'Receive the Holy Spirit.\'" The Greek <em>enephysēsen</em> (breathed into / on) is used in the LXX at Genesis 2:7: "the LORD God formed a man from the dust of the ground and breathed into his nostrils the breath of life, and the man became a living being." The resurrection is the new creation; the risen Christ is the new Adam; the breathing of the Spirit on the disciples is the new creation\'s constitutive act. As the first creation required the divine breath to make humans living beings, the new creation requires the Spirit-breath of the risen Christ to make disciples the new humanity. The Fourth Gospel\'s Pentecost happens at the resurrection appearance.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "If you forgive anyone\'s sins, their sins are forgiven; if you do not forgive them, they are not forgiven." The authority to declare forgiveness is given to the community constituted by the Spirit-breath of the risen Christ. This is not the community generating forgiveness from itself but declaring the forgiveness that the Son has accomplished through the cross. The word <em>tetelestai</em> — "it is finished" — is the basis of all subsequent declaration of forgiveness; the disciples forgive as heralds of the completed work, not as independent sources of grace. The keys of the kingdom (Matt 16:19) are the same authority stated in Johannine terms.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "Now Thomas (also known as Didymus), one of the Twelve, was not with the disciples when Jesus came." The absence of Thomas is the setup for the second appearance and the Christological climax of chapter 20. The Evangelist presents Thomas as the representative of all who have not seen the risen Christ and must believe on the testimony of those who have — which is the situation of every subsequent reader of the Gospel (v29). Thomas\'s absence is providential: it creates the occasion for the most explicit Christological confession in the Gospel.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "Unless I see the nail marks in his hands and put my finger where the nails were, and put my hand into his side, I will not believe." Thomas\'s demand for tactile evidence — not merely visual but physical contact with the wounds — is the most rigorous evidence standard in the resurrection narratives. He will not accept secondhand report; he requires direct experience. The Evangelist does not condemn Thomas\'s doubt but presents it as the honest response of one who has not yet encountered the risen Christ. Jesus will meet him exactly where he is (v27) and offer him exactly the evidence he requested.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "A week later... Jesus came and stood among them." The risen Christ returns to the locked room specifically for Thomas. The repetition of the appearance a week later — on the first day of the following week, the second Sunday — is the beginning of the pattern that will become Sunday worship: the risen Christ appears to his gathered community on the first day of the week. The church will continue to gather on the first day of the week in anticipation of the encounter with the risen Christ that the disciples experienced. Thomas is included in the second appearance as the representative of all absent believers who need their own encounter.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "Put your finger here; see my hands. Reach out your hand and put it into my side. Stop doubting and believe." The risen Christ\'s invitation to Thomas is the Evangelist\'s most concentrated statement of the incarnational reality of the resurrection: the same body that was crucified, the same hands that were nailed, the same side that was pierced, is here and available for physical examination. The resurrection is not a spiritual event that bypasses the body; it is the physical body of the crucified Son brought through death into indestructible life. The invitation to touch the wounds is the invitation to faith grounded in the reality of the incarnation and the passion.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: "My Lord and my God!" Thomas\'s confession is the highest Christological statement in the Gospel — higher even than Peter\'s "Messiah, the Son of the living God" (Matt 16:16), higher than Nathanael\'s "Son of God... King of Israel" (1:49). <em>Kyrios</em> and <em>theos</em> — Lord and God — applied to the risen Jesus who stands before him with the wounds of the cross: this is the confession that the Prologue\'s first verse ("the Word was God") has been building toward, that the seven "I am" statements have prepared for, that the trial before Pilate ironically enacted, and that the cross\'s inscription proclaimed. The one who had to die to be believed has died and is believed as Lord and God.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: "Because you have seen me, you have believed; blessed are those who have not seen and yet have believed." The beatitude on those who believe without seeing is addressed directly across the text to every subsequent reader of the Gospel. The Evangelist\'s Gospel is written precisely for this class of believers (v31): those who have not seen the risen Christ in person but who encounter him through the testimony of the Beloved Disciple. The beatitude is not a lesser blessing — Thomas receives it as a statement about those who come after him. The faith that rests on the testimony of the resurrection witnesses is the form of faith available to all who come after Easter, and Jesus declares it blessed.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "Jesus performed many other signs in the presence of his disciples, which are not recorded in this book." The Evangelist\'s acknowledgment of the incompleteness of the Gospel is his testimony to the inexhaustibility of Christ. The seven signs he has selected are representative, not exhaustive. The selection principle is v31: these particular signs were chosen because they most effectively accomplish the Gospel\'s purpose. The unrecorded signs are not more important than the recorded ones; the recorded ones were chosen for their power to produce and sustain the faith that the Gospel commends.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A direct revelation: "But these are written that you may believe that Jesus is the Messiah, the Son of God, and that by believing you may have life in his name." The Evangelist\'s purpose statement is the Christological thesis of the entire Gospel stated in its simplest and most comprehensive form. The Gospel has been arguing for this claim since 1:1; every sign, every discourse, every controversy, every "I am" statement, the trial, the crucifixion, the resurrection appearances — all of it is oriented toward this: that Jesus is the Messiah, the Son of God. The result of this faith is not merely correct belief but <em>zōē</em> — life in the fullest sense — in his name. The Gospel ends where it began: with the Word who is life (1:4).</p>'
  },
  "21": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: "Afterward Jesus appeared again to his disciples, by the Sea of Galilee." The third resurrection appearance (v14) moves from Jerusalem to Galilee — the region of the ministry\'s beginning, the place of calling and commissioning. The appearance by the sea echoes the original calling of the disciples in the Synoptics (Matt 4:18–22; Mark 1:16–20), bringing the Gospel\'s narrative arc full circle: from the calling of disciples by the sea, through the ministry, the passion, and the resurrection, back to the sea. The Evangelist\'s epilogue is a commission that returns to the site of the calling so that the disciples understand their mission as the continuation and extension of the ministry they witnessed.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: the seven disciples present — Simon Peter, Thomas, Nathanael, the sons of Zebedee, and two unnamed others — include the doubter who confessed (Thomas, v28), the one who will be three-times denied and restored (Peter), and the one from Cana where the first sign was performed (Nathanael, 2:1–11; 1:45–51). The Evangelist assembles the epilogue\'s cast from the Gospel\'s significant figures, closing the narrative circle that began with the calling of Nathanael and the wedding at Cana.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "but that night they caught nothing." The disciples\' return to fishing — their pre-call occupation — without Christ\'s direction produces nothing. The night catch is the figure of fruitlessness apart from union with Christ (15:5 — "apart from me you can do nothing"). The Evangelist uses the empty nets to create the context in which the risen Christ\'s direction transforms futility into abundance. The disciples are not condemned for going fishing; they are given the opportunity to experience again, in the resurrection context, what they experienced at the first calling: their fishing is inadequate; the Lord\'s direction is not.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "Early in the morning, Jesus stood on the shore, but the disciples did not realize that it was Jesus." The morning non-recognition parallels Mary\'s non-recognition in the garden (20:14). The risen Christ is present on the shore before the disciples are aware of him; he comes to them in their frustration and exhaustion. The Evangelist\'s pattern is consistent: the risen Christ appears to disciples who are not looking for him — Mary weeping at the tomb, disciples behind locked doors, fishermen returning empty. The resurrection appearances are initiated by the risen Christ, not produced by the disciples\' expectation.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "Friends, haven\'t you any fish?" The risen Christ\'s question — "do you have any food to eat?" (<em>prosphagion</em>, literally something eaten with bread, particularly fish) — is the opening of the engagement. The answer "No" is the honest acknowledgment of the empty nets that will be the occasion for the miraculous catch. The Evangelist\'s address <em>paidia</em> (children / lads) is affectionate — the same term used in 1 John 2:14, 18. The risen Christ engages his disciples in their ordinary failure with gentle interrogation that is the beginning of provision.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct type: "Throw your net on the right side of the boat and you will find some." The miraculous catch of fish that follows the risen Christ\'s direction deliberately echoes the call narrative in Luke 5:4–7, where the first miraculous catch of fish follows Jesus\' instruction and Peter\'s humble response. The Evangelist\'s epilogue creates a conscious parallel: at the beginning of the ministry, a miraculous catch of fish followed by a call to discipleship; at the end of the resurrection appearances, a miraculous catch of fish followed by a threefold commission (vv15–17). The parallel frames the entirety of the disciples\' call as the risen Christ\'s work from beginning to end.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "the disciple whom Jesus loved said to Peter, \'It is the Lord!\'" The Beloved Disciple again recognizes first (cf. 20:8 — believed at the empty tomb); Peter again acts first (cf. 20:6 — entered the tomb). The complementary pair functions together: the contemplative recognition of the Beloved Disciple and the impulsive action of Peter. That Peter wraps his outer garment around him before jumping into the water is an act of reverence: you do not approach the Lord naked (cf. Gen 3:21 — the need for covering in the presence of God). He clothes himself to meet the risen Christ on the shore.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: the other disciples follow in the boat, towing the full net. They cannot leave the net — the abundance of the catch makes it impossible to abandon. The net full of fish that cannot be hauled in (v6) is the harvest of the mission that the disciples cannot accomplish by themselves but drag toward shore by the risen Christ\'s direction. The community of disciples together — some in the water, some in the boat — bring the catch to the shore where the Lord awaits. The church\'s mission is accomplished not by individual heroism but by the community moving together toward the Christ who is already at the destination.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct revelation: "they saw a fire of burning coals there with fish on it, and some bread." <em>Anthrakia</em> (charcoal fire) appears in only two places in the entire NT: John 18:18, where Peter warms himself by a charcoal fire in the high priest\'s courtyard and denies Jesus three times; and here, John 21:9, where the risen Christ has prepared a charcoal fire for breakfast. The Evangelist\'s precise choice of vocabulary is the signal that the breakfast by the sea is the scene of Peter\'s restoration. The same kind of fire at which Peter denied becomes the fire at which he will be restored. The risen Christ has prepared the scene — fire, fish, bread — for the triple commission that will answer the triple denial.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "Bring some of the fish you have just caught." The risen Christ invites the disciples to contribute to the meal from the catch that his direction has made possible. The pattern is Eucharistic: the risen Christ who provides — as at the feeding of the five thousand (6:11 — "Jesus then took the loaves, gave thanks, and distributed to those who were seated") — also incorporates the disciples\' labor into the provision. The five loaves and two fish that the disciples brought to Jesus for the feeding of the multitude are echoed here: the disciples\' catch joins the fish the Lord has already prepared.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "So Simon Peter climbed back into the boat and dragged the net ashore. It was full of large fish, 153, but even with so many the net was not torn." The 153 fish has generated extensive allegorical speculation (Jerome: 153 species of fish = the totality of nations; Augustine: mathematical symbolism). The Evangelist offers no interpretive key and the Evangelist rarely includes numerically precise details without purpose (6:19 — twenty-five or thirty stadia; 11:39 — "four days"). Whatever the number signifies, two details are certain: the catch is enormous, and the net is not torn. In 10:16, Jesus spoke of "one flock"; in 15:1–8, he spoke of the branches remaining in the vine producing fruit. The net that holds the enormous catch without tearing is the community of disciples that the mission will produce — held together by the one who is the vine, the shepherd, the risen Lord who directs the nets.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "Come and have breakfast." The risen Christ\'s invitation to the meal is an act of extraordinary intimacy — the sharing of food as the restoration of fellowship. The disciples "knew it was the Lord" without needing to be told, yet "none of the disciples dared ask him, \'Who are you?\'" The reverential certainty is the post-resurrection experience of knowing the risen Christ: he is familiar and yet different, recognizable and yet beyond ordinary familiarity. The breakfast on the shore is the enacted form of the promise in Revelation 3:20: "I will come in and eat with that person, and they with me."</p>',
    "13": '<p>A shadow: "Jesus came, took the bread and gave it to them, and did the same with the fish." The action — taking bread, giving it to them — echoes the feeding of the five thousand (6:11: "Jesus then took the loaves, gave thanks, and distributed to those who were seated") and the Last Supper tradition preserved in the Synoptics. The Evangelist presents the risen Christ\'s breakfast distribution as the continuation of the same pattern: the one who fed the multitude with five loaves feeds his disciples with bread and fish on the resurrection morning. The Eucharistic resonance is present without being forced: every meal the risen Christ shares with his disciples carries the weight of the one meal that gathered all the significance of his life and death.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "This was now the third time Jesus appeared to his disciples after he was raised from the dead." The Evangelist\'s counting — third appearance — marks the completeness of the resurrection witness. Three witnesses establish a matter (Deut 19:15); three appearances to the gathered disciples establish the resurrection as a reality among them. The third appearance, like the third day of the resurrection and the threefold restoration of Peter that follows, carries the number of completion and fullness. The resurrection has been fully demonstrated; the disciples are fully equipped; the commission will be complete.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: "Simon son of John, do you love me more than these?" The triple question — "do you love me?" asked three times — directly and deliberately reverses the triple denial at the charcoal fire of 18:17–27. The Evangelist\'s structural symmetry is precise: three denials at a charcoal fire / three affirmations at a charcoal fire. The name "Simon son of John" — the pre-call name before Jesus renamed him Peter (1:42) — recalls the man before the call, the man who will now be re-commissioned. The question uses <em>agapaō</em> (love as moral commitment and devotion); Peter responds with <em>phileō</em> (love as personal affection). Whether the Evangelist intends a sharp distinction or is using the terms as near-synonyms is disputed; at minimum, Peter does not match the level of the question but offers what he genuinely has.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "Again Jesus said, \'Simon son of John, do you love me?\'" The second question — the second of the three that will undo the three denials — is asked without the comparative ("more than these"). Jesus removes the implicit comparison with the other disciples; the question now is simply about Peter\'s own love for the Son. The commission this time is to "take care of my sheep" — the shepherding language of chapter 10 (the Good Shepherd) is given to Peter as the task that flows from love for the shepherd. Peter is not replacing the Good Shepherd; he is exercising under-shepherding derived from and accountable to the one who lays down his life for the sheep.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: "The third time he said to him, \'Simon son of John, do you love me?\' Peter was hurt because Jesus asked him the third time." The third question uses <em>phileō</em> — the word Peter has been using — as if now meeting Peter at his own level. Peter\'s hurt is the recognition that the three questions have been as deliberate as the three denials. The restoration is being performed with surgical precision: each denial is being addressed, each "I don\'t know the man" is being answered with "you know that I love you." The final commission — "Feed my sheep" — restores Peter to the apostolic vocation that his denial had seemingly forfeited. The grace of the risen Christ is not the grace that overlooks failure but the grace that restores through a deliberate repetition of the failure\'s form.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct revelation: "when you are old you will stretch out your hands, and someone else will dress you and lead you where you do not want to go." The prophecy of Peter\'s martyrdom — interpreted explicitly in v19 — uses the language of crucifixion: "stretch out your hands" is the posture of one being bound to a cross. The early church understood Peter\'s death by crucifixion (Clement of Rome, Tertullian) as the fulfillment of this word. Jesus\' prophecy to Peter at the restoration is simultaneously the prediction of his martyrdom — the most extreme form of the discipleship to which "follow me" calls. The one who denied to avoid death is called to follow into death. The denial at the charcoal fire becomes the cross that Peter will embrace.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct revelation: "Jesus said this to indicate the kind of death by which Peter would glorify God. Then he said to him, \'Follow me!\'" The Evangelist\'s editorial comment — "to indicate the kind of death by which Peter would glorify God" — is the Christological interpretation of martyrdom: the disciple\'s death glorifies God in the same way the Son\'s death glorified God (12:23, 28; 13:31). The martyr\'s death is the ultimate form of following the shepherd who lays down his life (10:11, 15), the seed that falls to the ground and dies (12:24), and the one who loved his own to the end (13:1). "Follow me" at the end of the Gospel is the same call as at the beginning (1:43 — "Follow me"); now Peter knows what following means and accepts it.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "Peter turned and saw that the disciple whom Jesus loved was following them." The Beloved Disciple is the witness to Peter\'s restoration just as he was the witness to the crucifixion (19:26–27) and the empty tomb (20:8). His presence in the epilogue is the Evangelist\'s way of maintaining the testimony-chain: Peter\'s restoration and commission are witnessed by the same disciple whose testimony grounds the Gospel. The Beloved Disciple\'s following is both physical (walking behind them) and the deeper following that the Gospel commends: the discipleship of witness and contemplation that will produce the Gospel itself (v24).</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "Lord, what about him?" Peter\'s question — immediately after receiving the commission and the prophecy of his martyrdom — is the instinctive comparison of one\'s own calling with another\'s. The Evangelist presents this as the natural but misdirected response to a personal call: instead of receiving it fully, Peter looks at the Beloved Disciple and wonders if he will have a different fate. The question is answered with the rebuke that serves all subsequent disciples who compare their vocations with others\': "what is that to you? You must follow me."</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "If I want him to remain alive until I return, what is that to you? You must follow me." The risen Christ\'s sovereignty over the vocations and destinies of his disciples — the martyr and the witness, Peter and the Beloved Disciple — is the final word on discipleship in the Gospel. Peter will die for the Lord; the Beloved Disciple will live to write the testimony. Both are acts of following; neither is superior to the other; both are the Lord\'s to determine. The last word the risen Christ speaks to Peter about discipleship is "follow me" — the same word he spoke at the first call (1:43). The Gospel ends where it began: with the call to follow the Son.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "the rumor spread among the believers that this disciple would not die." The community\'s misunderstanding of Jesus\' conditional statement — "if I want him to remain until I return" is not a promise that he would remain — is the Evangelist\'s final reminder of how easily the community constructs its own expectations around the words of Jesus rather than receiving them as they are. The Evangelist corrects the misunderstanding directly, modeling the hermeneutical discipline the Gospel itself has been practicing: do not read more into the words of Jesus than the words themselves carry. The correction of this misunderstanding is itself an act of faithful witness.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation: "This is the disciple who testifies to these things and who wrote them down. We know that his testimony is true." The Beloved Disciple is identified as the author of the Gospel\'s testimony — the eyewitness at the cross (19:35), the one who first believed at the empty tomb (20:8), the one who recognized the risen Christ on the shore (21:7). The "we know" of the final verse is the community\'s endorsement of the testimony — the elders of the Johannine community confirming the witness that has been preserved. The Gospel rests on the eyewitness testimony of one who was present at the critical moments of the passion, resurrection, and restoration. The Beloved Disciple\'s testimony is not secondhand; it is the foundation of the community\'s faith.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "Jesus did many other things as well. If every one of them were written down, I suppose that even the whole world would not have room for the books that would be written." The closing hyperbole is the Evangelist\'s final testimony to the inexhaustibility of the incarnate Son. The Gospel has selected from an infinite supply; what has been written is sufficient for faith (20:31); what has not been written is beyond the capacity of the world to contain. The figure is not mere rhetorical flourish — it is the Evangelist\'s statement about who Christ is: the one whose acts and words overflow every container, whose life cannot be exhausted by any text, any canon, any world. John 1:1 began "in the beginning was the Word"; John 21:25 ends by acknowledging that the Word\'s story cannot be ended. The Gospel that could not contain the Logos stops not because the story is over but because the story is inexhaustible.</p>'
  }
}

